</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=lest>Lest</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 82<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/26/02 10:48:51 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2204.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> trucking with evil</span><hr size=1> I actually wrote a bit in Bard for a Day on this a while back, after buying a low level weapon from a certain (in)famous gnomish necromancer -<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showMessage?topicID=247.topic">pub94.ezboard.com/ffirion...=247.topic</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
(Now, I could have just said &quot;he's a gnome -- I can buy from him.&quot; But the chap showed up in a black robe carrying a scythe. Not much doubt to his profession...)<br>
<br>
I figure there are (at least) two *equally valid* ways to roleplay the good/evil thing, and I sure as hell don't want to defend or debate either (so please please pretty please don't flame me too badly). <br>
<br>
The first is along race lines: this is sword and sorcery fantasy, where there is Good and Evil. Where races are precisely what they should be, good, evil, chaotic, lawful, whatever. They just ARE, and one should roleplay accordingly. <br>
<br>
The other way is to play tabula rasa, and see folks as individuals. Lest, he's never met an ogre before. Met one troll, who, while he did look a bit... hungry... was extremely polite and chatty rather than combative. He has also met a LOT of snobby, greedy, and /or just plain rude wood elves. And a few very sweet ones as well. (Never met a barbarian he didn't like, though. For the record.)<br>
<br>
Anyway -- Lest's a half-breed outcast loner with quite a bit of self-loathing going on. He's not in any position to judge anyone, so he takes each person as they are. If you have something he needs or he has something you need, he'll trade with anyone once -- he wants to learn your name, and the value of your soul. <br>
<br>
Plus it's honestly the only way the poor bastard gets to meet new people most of the time anyway. <br>
<br>
Just my, um, 4 coppers. Sorry for rambling. <br>
<br>
Lest <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=morgrist>Morgrist</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 310<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/26/02 11:16:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2204.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: trucking with evil</span><hr size=1> I am a knight of Innoruuk.<br>
 <br>
I ain't here ta pour coin in some lightlover's pouch. I ain't here ta make their life easy cause they can bribe me wit' platinum,neither.<br>
<br>
Which happens ta be why I ain't a Leaguer no more-cause I won't be part of a group that makes em fat an' happy.<br>
<br>
There ain't nothin' a gods-fearin' follower of t'dark gods needs from one who don't follow em-aside from their deaths.<br>
 <br>
Anyone who sayin otherwise is putting their greed ahead o' their faith-an' I say it goes fer almost any who ain't godless heathens. Ya enrich t'followers of a god,ya increase that god's power on Norrath by empowerin' their followers.<br>
 <br>
I burn Tunarean wood-prayers when I find em. Iffen I find any thing sacred ta lightlovin' gods,it's broken an' ashes when I'm done with it-fer it's cleansin Norrath of weakness. An' any fool that gets his hands on somethin' sacred ta MY god that doesn't deserves what he gets iffen I get it soon after,if he ain't faithful ta t'right gods.<br>
 <br>
Tradin' with infidels means yer just makin' it worse fer yer people an' yer god ta do what they desire in Norrath. T'paladin ya sell to today is going ta' be &quot;cleansing Norrath&quot; wit' yer help tomorrow. That druid ya sold somethin' to will be reavin' and banditry in Nektulos that much easier thanks ta yer trades.<br>
 <br>
-Morgrist Vanadil<br>
